h3. Problem Definition

During reindexing, an 'Unable to index custom date field' message is logged when a custom date field for an issue has an invalid value, but the Id of the issue is not recorded.
{code:java}
2012-06-25 23:30:58,073 IssueIndexer:thread-6 WARN admin 1406x194x2 1hi7f6 165.222.16.87,165.222.100.83 /secure/admin/IndexReIndex.jspa [index.indexers.impl.NumberCustomFieldIndexer] Unable to index custom date field 'Date of First Response(customfield_10267) with value: -61811600400000
{code}
Logging the Id of the affected issue when this message gets generated would help save time correcting the invalid value.
h3. Suggested Solution

Log affected Issue Ids for 'Unable to index custom date field' messages generated during reindexing operations.
h3. Workaround

If there's only a single issue with an invalid value, the problematic issue can be found by utilizing a SQL query:
{code:sql}
select * from customfieldvalue where customfield={customFieldId} order by datevalue asc limit 1;
{code}
  !https://confluence.atlassian.com/s/en_GB/7901/af536c7c6dffcc1d697b914b797aa7f2f306b4f8/_/images/icons/emoticons/information.svg!  Replace \{customFieldId} with the Id of the custom date field logged in the WARN message
  
 Another workaround for finding the invalid value is detailed in [Reindexing fails with Unable to index custom date field error in Jira server|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/reindexing-fails-with-unable-to-index-custom-date-field-error-in-jira-server-294488445.html]:
{quote}To find the invalid date you must run the SQL query below in your database:
{code:sql}
select * from customfieldvalue where customfield = <CUSTOM_FIELD_ID> and datevalue < '1970-01-01';
{code}
{code:sql}
 select issueid, created from jiraaction where actiontype='comment' and created < '1970-01-01';
{code}
!https://confluence.atlassian.com/s/en_GB/7901/af536c7c6dffcc1d697b914b797aa7f2f306b4f8/_/images/icons/emoticons/information.svg!  The <CUSTOM_FIELD_ID> in the above query can be found in the error code as part of the string: "customfield_10267"
{quote}

As a JIRA Admin and Project Admin, customers want the possibility of completely stopping the notifications from coming up when we have "wrong permissions" configured.

For example, as a use case:

{quote}
Customers sometimes have the "Browse Project Permission" not mapped to a project role. They only assign this permission to directory groups or single service accounts added manually. 

Currently JIRA shows up a message saying that the Browse Projects permission is not assigned to a project role and allows them to fix the problem. But there's times when a user becomes a new project admin and it starts receiving this notifications and hit the button "fixing the issue", but configuring things not accordingly to what the company wants.
{quote}


h3. Existing Workaround:

Adding the following code into an Announcement Banner on JIRA will hide all the notifications that can be closed on JIRA:

{code}
<style type="text/css">
#announcement-banner {
  padding: 0px !important;
  border-bottom: none !important;
}
.aui-flag .aui-message.closeable{display:none;}
</style>
{code}

(!) *Note*: This will hide all the messages that are configured under a HTML div with the following classes and also the Announcement Banner itself:

{code}
<div class="aui-message closeable">...</div>
{code}

h3. Current State:

In Jira Data Center, the search index is replicated between nodes automatically through the shared home. This process adds logging to track the progress – for example:
{code:java}
ClusterMessageHandlerServiceThread:thread-1 INFO      [c.a.j.index.ha.DefaultIndexRecoveryManager] Restoring search indexes - 20% complete... Restored index backup
{code}
When this process completes, the following message is logged:
{code:java}
ClusterMessageHandlerServiceThread:thread-1 INFO      [c.a.j.index.ha.DefaultIndexRecoveryManager] Recovering search indexes - 100% complete... Recovered all indexes
{code}
However, the restore can fail between these two points and the initial message {{Restored index backup}} is misleading as it indicates the snapshot restore is complete at this time.
h3. Suggested Improvement:

Remove or change the message {{Restored index backup}} within the logs to indicate the restore is not complete.
